type="local"
addr="larsbirkedal">Lars Birkedal</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00OI</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Most practical programming languages have <fr:strong><fr:em>side effects</fr:em></fr:strong>: state, input-output, errors, etc.</fr:p><beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer"></beamer:pause><fr:p><fr:strong><fr:em>Monads</fr:em></fr:strong> capture the structure of side effects (<fr:link
href="moggi-1991.xml"
type="local"
addr="moggi-1991">Moggi</fr:link>, <fr:link
href="philipwadler.xml"
type="local"
addr="philipwadler">Wadler</fr:link>). </fr:p>
 <jms-indent:block
xmlns:jms-indent="jonmsterling:indenting">
  
 <jms-indent:row>
   <fr:tex>\mathsf {T} \colon   \mathbf {type} \to \mathbf {type}</fr:tex>
  </jms-indent:row>

  
 <jms-indent:row>
   <fr:tex>\mathsf {ret} \colon   \mathsf {T} \, {A} \to \mathsf {T} \, {A}</fr:tex>
  </jms-indent:row>

  
 <jms-indent:row>
   <fr:tex>\mathsf {bind} \colon   \mathsf {T} \, B \to   { \mathopen {} \left ( A \to \mathsf {T} \, B \right ) \mathclose {}} \to   \mathsf {T} \, B</fr:tex>
  </jms-indent:row>

 </jms-indent:block>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
