type="local"
addr="larsbirkedal">Lars Birkedal</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00OI</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Our main observation is that a slight variation on <fr:link
href="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2022.xml"
type="local"
addr="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2022">SGB’22</fr:link> suffices to model univalent reference types, <html:mark
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">so long as both <fr:tex>\mathbf {FinSet}</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>\mathbf {Set}</fr:tex> are both univalent universes</html:mark> in the sense of Voevodsky.</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>Univalence of <fr:tex>\mathbf {FinSet}</fr:tex> implies the <fr:strong>LAYOUT UNIVALENCE</fr:strong> rule.</fr:li>
  <fr:li>Univalence of <fr:tex>\mathbf {Set}</fr:tex> implies the <fr:strong>CELL UNIVALENCE</fr:strong> rule.</fr:li></fr:ol><fr:p>We therefore need an impredicative version of <fr:strong><fr:em>guarded <fr:link
href="hottbook.xml"
type="local"
addr="hottbook"><html:mark
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">homotopy</html:mark> type theory</fr:link></fr:em></fr:strong>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2012</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Slide</fr:taxon><fr:addr>#471</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-471.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Impredicative Guarded Homotopy Type Theory</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>10</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:author><fr:link
href="danielgratzer.xml"
type="local"
addr="danielgratzer">Daniel Gratzer</fr:link></fr:author><fr:author><fr:link
href="larsbirkedal.xml"
type="local"
addr="larsbirkedal">Lars Birkedal</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00OI</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We define <fr:strong>iGHoTT</fr:strong> to be the extension of Martin-Löf’s intensional type theory by the following additional features:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>homotopy type theory: the univalence axiom</fr:li>
  <fr:li>guarded recursion: later modality <fr:tex>\mathord { \blacktriangleright }</fr:tex> and solutions to guarded fixed points</fr:li>
  <fr:li>a univalent impredicative universe, <fr:em>i.e.</fr:em> a universe <fr:tex>\mathcal {S} \in \mathcal {U}</fr:tex> closed under families of <fr:tex>\mathcal {S}</fr:tex>-small types indexed in a <fr:tex>\mathcal {U}</fr:tex>-small type.</fr:li></fr:ol><beamer:pause
xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer"></beamer:pause><fr:p>In <fr:strong>iGHoTT</fr:strong>, we can define a model of univalent reference types. The real question is whether we can find a model of <fr:strong>iGHoTT</fr:strong>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
