href="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2022.xml"
type="local"
addr="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2022">SGB’22</fr:link> were not the first to combine guarded recursion with realisability to model higher-order dynamic allocation; see <fr:link
href="birkedal-st%C3%B8vring-thamsborg-2010-realisability.xml"
type="local"
addr="birkedal-støvring-thamsborg-2010-realisability">Birkedal, Støvring, and Thamsborg (2010)</fr:link>.</fr:p><fr:p>However, <fr:em>op.cit.</fr:em> relied on a <fr:em>specific</fr:em> realisability model based on an untyped domain model of a stateful language; in contrast, the model construction of <fr:link
href="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2022.xml"
type="local"
addr="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2022">SGB’22</fr:link> applies uniformly for any pair <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( \mathcal {E}, \mathbb {O} \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>Thus <fr:link
href="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2022.xml"
type="local"
addr="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2022">SGB’22</fr:link> showed that realisability is inessential: if we find any other viable source of impredicative universes besides realisability, <fr:link
href="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2022.xml"
type="local"
addr="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2022">SGB’22</fr:link> would apply there too.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
